Stays on edge. It is close to 5.5% that is pretty certain. Current running 12 months average is 5.9%. It could drop to 5.5 or below, but then the August price changes need to drop significantly compared to July, which hasn't happened in the last years. So, I will up my estimate a little to 94%. But there remains a chance that the running 12 month average reduces to 5.5% or below. All that needs to happen is prices to more or less stay the same in August, and this is not unthinkable. So, I give that a 1 in 17 chance.

Core CPI at 5.9%, and has been trending down by approx 2-3pp since March (although steady in July). A 1.1pp increase, while not unprecedented, would seem to require a significant shock on the level of the Russian invasion of Ukraine (which seems very unlikely). Meanwhile, a decrease of more than 0.4% seems unlikely given that the only time the CPI has only gone down that much once in the last 20 years and that was during the hight of the Covid-19 pandemic in the US.

Rethinking seasonality some more. We've already seen 5.43% inflation in the past 10 months, with mom inflation >0.5%, so I think <5.5% is out. If mom inflation stays <= May-June mom inflation, then inflation will be <7.0%. In recent years, inflation has typically been steepest in the first half of the year, flattens roughly from May through July or August, has a small peak in Oct, and stays flat or falls through Dec. This general pattern held even in 2021, albeit superimposed on a big growth trend. So I feel much more confident that Aug inflation will stay in bin 4.@JPH

Index at 290.846 for April 22, 279.507 for Aug 21. (290.846/279.507 - 1) * 100% = 4.06% over 8 months. 4 more months to go.Index at 289.305 for March 22. (290.846/289.305 - 1) * 100% = 0.53% mom inflation.https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPILFENSAt 0.53% mom inflation, we'd expect to see 2.14% inflation from April through August, and annual inflation in Aug to be at 6.3%.To reach 7.0%, the index would need to reach 279.507*1.07 = 299.072 in August. That would require (299.072/290.846 -1) * 100% = 2.83% inflation from April to August, equivalent to 0.70% mom inflation. Given that we saw 0.53% mom inflation in the index for April, it seems unlikely (but not impossible) that we'd see 0.70% mom from now to August.

The Biden administration is bracing for the Labor Departments consumer price index report to show that inflation is extraordinarily elevated. The consumer price index, or CPI, is one of Wall Streets favorite ways to measure inflation. The CPI reading for March 2022 is due out Tuesday morning. We expect March CPI headline inflation to be extraordinarily elevated due to Putins price hike, said White House press secretary Jen Psaki. The February reading showed the benchmark index rose 7.9% over the last 12 months, the highest level since 1982.

Oops! We're looking at *core* inflation in this question. Revising from my previous forecast.

Here are the CPI values historically: https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS Aug 2021: 273.567 Jan 2022: 281.148 So there has already been 2.77% inflation in the first 5 months of the year to Aug 22. At this pace, by June 22 (5 months from now), inflation would be 1.0277 * 1.0277 = 1.056 => 5.6% -- with 2 months left to go. If there is 0.5% inflation in the remaining 2 months of the forecast, then the 12-month inflation in Aug 22 would be 1.056 * 1.005 * 1.005 = 1.0668 => 6.7%. With inflation in the last 2 months at 0.6%, it would be 1.056 * 1.006 * 1.006 = 1.0687 => 6.9%.

With persistent inflation in core commodities and supply chain shortages expected to continue, we should see a rise in Core inflation as well with a lag to the CPI. To arrive at base rates, calculated the implied increase in the index needed for each bin, assigning probabilities with an upward bias, given my assumption of core inflation being a lagged index to CPI. https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPILFESL
